run: release
---

# Release

Gates the tree, syncs every manifest to `version` via `@tools/version`, then
commits, tags `vX.Y.Z`, and pushes. The pushed tag is what the release CI
(`.github/workflows/release.yml`) builds the prebuilt binaries from — there is no
`cargo publish` step; the binaries *are* the release.

It composes `@tools/gate` and `@tools/version` at runtime through `jd` (the
pipeable entry point) rather than cross-file `just` deps, which `jd … --justfile`
does not inline. `@tools/gate` runs first — a red gate aborts before anything is
bumped or pushed — then `@tools/version` syncs every manifest. `version` is
required and must be `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`. Write the `CHANGELOG.md` entry **before**
running this (the `/release` command does that for you); the commit picks it up.

```just
release version:
  #!/usr/bin/env sh
  set -eu
  case "{{version}}" in
    [0-9]*.[0-9]*.[0-9]*) ;;
    *) echo "version must be MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH, got '{{version}}'" >&2; exit 1 ;;
  esac
  jd get tools_gate    --justfile | just --justfile - gate
  jd get tools_version --justfile | just --justfile - bump {{version}}
  git add CHANGELOG.md Cargo.toml Cargo.lock
  git commit -m "chore: release v{{version}}"
  git tag -a "v{{version}}" -m "v{{version}}"
  git push --follow-tags
```
